Experiences/Reflection:
Nearly every web-based application has a database of some kind. However, the
choice of database can be daunting. There are hundreds of different databases, each
with their own benefits and drawbacks.
A polyglot database is more than one database used under a backend. The goal of a
polyglot database is that each database compliments the others. This way, we only see
the benefits of each database.
Relational Database
• Stores data in tables called relations
• Examples: PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite

Normally, an application only contains one database, chosen for it benefits to the
project. However, as the application and and features grow, the drawbacks of the
chosen database become more noticeable. So, how do we prevent a database from
failing to its drawbacks?
The solution: a polyglot database

There are many more database types. However, using the 4 architectures above. We
will be building a ecommerce app. Where users can purchase products. The databases
will record users, products, and transactions. Doing this, we can make each of the
architectures perform in the best way it can.
Polyglot databases are often more work than they are worth. Every
query a computer makes takes an unpredictable amount of time which,
on small datasets like ours, takes longer than it would with just one
database. However, on large datasets, it can quite useful. Facebook, for
example, uses 6 different databases in their architecture, and many
other tech giants use polyglot databases.
One downfall we saw during our development was the over-
complication of queries. When creating an object, we made 4 different
queries to our databases, each dependent on the previous one. Leading
to a messy chain of Promises — which is a JavaScript object used to
handle asynchronous actions, like querys.
Many things did go well, however. The use of each database was applied
well. Thanks to MongoDB, the frontend pages were easy and fast to set
up. Using Neo4J, what would have been a complicated algorithm was one
query. Redis, worked well as a cache, and to sync up values, like
incremental ID's between databases.
